  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Every property in Brisbane sits within a zone defined by Brisbane City Council's City Plan. Zoning determines what can be built on the land, what activities are permitted, and how much density is allowed. Most sellers do not think deeply about zoning until a buyer or their solicitor raises a question about it during due diligence. Understanding your zoning before you list puts you in a much stronger position: you can market the development potential honestly to the right buyers, and you can anticipate and answer the questions that informed buyers will ask.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to check your property's zoning</h2>
      <p>The primary tool for checking Brisbane property zoning is PD Online, Brisbane City Council's planning and development portal. You can search by address and view your property's zone, overlays, and any relevant codes that apply. Your agent can also confirm zoning from their own research tools. The key point is to check before you list, not after a buyer raises a question, because the zoning information shapes both how you position the property and which buyer segments you actively market to.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The main residential zones in Brisbane's inner east</h2>
      <p>For sellers in Brisbane's inner-east suburbs, the zones you are most likely to encounter are Low Density Residential, Low-Medium Density Residential, Medium Density Residential, and Character Residential. Each sits within Brisbane City Plan 2014 and determines what is permissible as of right versus what requires development application approval.</p>

      <p>Low Density Residential is the most common zone for traditional suburban homes in suburbs like Camp Hill, Carina, Norman Park, and Seven Hills. It is designed for detached houses, with duplexes and dual occupancies permissible in some circumstances depending on lot size and frontage. Development beyond a single dwelling generally requires council approval and is not guaranteed. The ceiling price for a Low Density Residential property is typically set by its value as a home, not by its development potential.</p>

      <p>Low-Medium Density Residential permits a broader range of housing types, including townhouses, duplexes, and small multi-unit developments, subject to meeting the relevant codes. Properties in this zone often attract developer and investor interest alongside owner-occupier demand. The presence of development potential is a genuine marketing point, provided you do not overstate what is actually permissible without approval.</p>

      <p>Medium Density Residential allows for apartment buildings and higher-density residential development, subject to applicable codes and any relevant overlays. Properties in this zone in good inner-city locations can attract developer premiums well above what the existing house would achieve as a standalone sale. Identifying and marketing to that buyer segment is a distinct skill, and your agent's experience with development site sales matters here.</p>

      <p>Character Residential is a zone that applies to many traditional Queensland homes in the inner east, and it deserves particular attention from sellers. It is explained in more detail below.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The Character Residential overlay and what it means for sellers</h2>
      <p>The Character Residential zone and the Traditional Building Character overlay are different but related concepts that affect many homes in suburbs like Hawthorne, Bulimba, Norman Park, and parts of Morningside and Coorparoo. Together, they impose restrictions on demolition and significant alterations to character homes, which Brisbane City Council defines as pre-1947 construction that contributes to the traditional streetscape.</p>

      <p>For sellers, the practical implication is that buyers who want to demolish and rebuild cannot do so as of right if the property falls within the overlay. Council approval is required, and approval is not automatic. This affects the developer buyer pool directly: knockdown-rebuild buyers are constrained, and some will step back from bidding as a result. What remains is a buyer pool of renovators, owner-occupiers who love the character of the home, and developers who have experience navigating the approval process.</p>

      <p>Paradoxically, the Character overlay can also support price in some circumstances. A well-maintained character home in a desirable inner-east suburb attracts buyers who are specifically seeking that type of property and are willing to pay a premium for it. The overlay creates scarcity. Character homes that are original, well-presented, and in streets of similar quality consistently achieve strong results with owner-occupier buyers who would not consider a modern home in the same location.</p>

      <p>The key for sellers is to understand clearly which category applies, disclose it to buyers upfront, and market to the buyer pool that values what your property actually offers rather than trying to attract buyers whose plans are likely to be frustrated by the overlay.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How zoning shapes your ceiling price</h2>
      <p>For properties in Low Density Residential zones without development overlays, the ceiling price is set by what a family or owner-occupier will pay for the home in its current or improved form. Zoning does not add to value; it simply does not constrain it in the way that a character overlay might.</p>

      <p>For properties with higher-density zoning or clear development potential, the ceiling price can be substantially above the "house value" because a developer buyer is modelling the end value of the project they can build on the site. The land becomes worth more than the existing improvement, which means the value conversation shifts from "what is the house worth" to "what can be built here and what is that worth." This is a different calculation, and most residential agents are not experienced at running it properly. If your property has genuine development potential, working with an agent who has transacted in that space matters.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers should disclose about zoning</h2>
      <p>Buyers and their advisers always check zoning. It is freely available through PD Online, and any buyer who is spending close to a million dollars or more on a Brisbane property will have their solicitor confirm the zoning position before settlement. There is no benefit in obscuring zoning information, and several risks in doing so.</p>

      <p>If a buyer proceeds on an assumption about development potential that is not supported by the actual zoning, the transaction can unravel at the due diligence stage, wasting everyone's time and cost. More seriously, if a seller or agent has made representations about development potential that are not accurate, there is exposure to misleading conduct claims. The straightforward approach is to confirm the zoning accurately, disclose it in the information memorandum or contract documents, and let buyers conduct their own planning due diligence from an accurate starting point.</p>

